are of course synonymes. 1110 Appareret: I find no other example of the use of this verb which is here very expressive: Faber compares the Greek προσκτᾶσθαι. caeli domus: VI 358 Concutitur caeli domus: he may have been thinking of Ennius' strange divum domus altisonum each: Aen. x 1 domus omnipotentis Olympi: but Lucretius' expression implies more : Hor. od. 11 12 8 Fulqens contremuit domus Saturni veteris. 1111 consurqeret: one can hardly say whether this is simply for surqeret, or, what is more graphio, for undique circum surqeret, or even suryeret una cum caelo. This formation of our world is much more fully de- lineated v 449-508: above, 1058—1063, he described the exordia of this world 3 here he pictures its completion. 1112 plaqis: these blows of atoms are, as we have so often seen before, the chief cause of the for- mation and conservation of things, by enabling the atoms to clash and try all kinds of union, until some suitable one is found. 1114 umor, ferra, iynes, aether are used here loosely and poetically for the elements fitted by their shape etc. to assist in forming water earth eto. 1115 procudunt, as 111 1081 N ec nova vivendo procuditur ulla voluptas; V 850 ,oropaqamlo procudere saecla3 856 propaqando procudere prolem. aethe· raque aether: for aeraque aer, since the poet here employs Empedocles for his own purpose, just as 991 foll. he made use of Anaxagoras and Euri- pides: Emped. 270 πυρὶ δ’ αὐξάνεται πῦρ, Αὔξει δὲ χθὼν μὲν σφέτερον δέ· μας αἰθέρα δ’ αῖθήρ; in form his vss. are rather a reminiscence of the more famous 321 Γαίῃ μὲν γὰρ γαῖαν ὀπώπαμεν ὕδατι δ’ ὕδωρ Αἷθέρι δ’ αἰθέρα δῖον, οἰτοὶρ πυρὶ πῦρ ἀίδηλονι elsewhere too Emped. thus uses αἰθήρ, as 105 Πῦρ καὶ ὕδωρ καὶ γαῖα καὶ αἰθέρος ἤπιον ὕψος, and 216. Lucr. has probably only followed Empedocles here 3 but see n. to 1 250 aether, where it is shewn that he sometimes uses the word strictly, sometimes for the upper regions generally and the seat of rain: thus in one place he has aetheriae nubes, in another innubilus aether, in a third aetherias auras. 1116 Donique: this form of donec recurs v 708, 723, 997, always before a vowel: Lucr. may in one or other place have written doneque, which in one place, v 708, A pr. m. exhibits. See too Val. Rose in Hermes 11 p. 468, who there and in his edition restores to Vitruvius doneque four times for the denique of mss, but he does not state the case quite fairly between donique and doneque, our oldest authority, an inscription, having as Huebner shews, donique.
